    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "Observation of the X(1840) in the 3(\u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 ) invariant mass in J/\u03c8 \u2192 \u03b33(\u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 ) at BESIII is reviewed. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "With a sample of 225.3 \u00d7 10 6 J/\u03c8 events collected with the BESIII detector at BEPCII, the X(1840) is observed with a statistical significance of 7.6\u03c3. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "The mass, width and product branching fraction of the X(1840) are determined. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "The decay \u03b7 \u2192 3(\u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 ) is searched for, and the upper limit of the branching fraction is set at the 90% confidence level.",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Introduction",
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Within the standard model framework, the strong interaction is described by Quantum Chromodynamics (QCD), which suggests the existence of the unconventional hadrons, such as glueballs, hybrid states and multiquark states. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The establishment of such states remains one of the main interests in experimental particle physics.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Decays of the J/\u03c8 particle are ideal for the study of the hadron spectroscopy and the searching for the unconventional hadrons. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "In the decays of the J/\u03c8 particle, several observations in the mass region 1.8 GeV/c 2 -1.9 GeV/c 2 have been presented in different experiments, [1][2][3][4][5][6][7][8] such as the X(pp), 1-3 X(1835), 4,5 X(1810) 6,7 and X(1870). ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
